/-!

# Equivalence extracting element from contraction

-/

open FieldSpecification
variable {𝓕 : FieldSpecification}

namespace WickContraction
variable {n : ℕ} (c : WickContraction n)
open PhysLean.List
open PhysLean.Fin
```

We're importing the necessary libraries and opening namespaces to access relevant definitions and lemmas.

Now, we'll define the equivalence lemma `extractEquiv`:

```tactics
lemma extractEquiv_equiv {c1 c2 : (c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted}
    (h : c1.1 = c2.1) (ho : c1.2 = uncontractedCongr (by rw [h]) c2.2) : c1 = c2 := by
  cases c1
  cases c2
  simp_all only [Sigma.mk.inj_iff]
  simp only at h
  subst h
  simp only [uncontractedCongr, Equiv.optionCongr_apply, heq_eq_eq, true_and]
  rename_i a
  match a with
  | none => simp
  | some a =>
    simp only [Option.map_some, Option.some.injEq]
    ext
    simp
```

This lemma is proving that if two elements `c1` and `c2` have the same set of pairs (i.e., `c1.1 = c2.1`) and their uncontracted sets are related by the congruence `uncontractedCongr` (which essentially means their uncontracted sets are the same up to the permutation defined by `h`), then `c1 = c2`. This is a technical lemma ensuring the equivalence relation is well-defined.

Now, we'll define the main equivalence `extractEquiv`:

```tactics
/-- The equivalence between `WickContraction n.succ` and the sigma type
  `(c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted` formed by inserting
  and erasing elements from a contraction. -/
def extractEquiv (i : Fin n.succ) : WickContraction n.succ ≃
    (c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted where
  toFun := fun c => ⟨erase c i, getDualErase c i⟩
  invFun := fun ⟨c, j⟩ => insertAndContractNat c i j
  left_inv f := by
    simp
  right_inv f := by
    refine extractEquiv_equiv ?_ ?_
    simp only [insertAndContractNat_erase]
    simp only [Nat.succ_eq_add_one]
    have h1 := insertAndContractNat_getDualErase f.fst i f.snd
    exact insertAndcontractNat_getDualErase _ i _
```

This defines the equivalence between `WickContraction (n+1)` and the sigma type `(c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted`. This is a key lemma establishing how contractions can be built up or broken down.

Next, we have a lemma about the uncontracted set when we have `none` as the second part of the sigma type:

```tactics
lemma extractEquiv_symm_none_uncontracted (i : Fin n.succ) (c : WickContraction n) :
    ((extractEquiv i).symm ⟨c, none⟩).uncontracted =
    (Insert.insert i (c.uncontracted.map i.succAboveEmb)) := by
  exact insertAndContractNat_none_uncontracted c i
```

This lemma is showing that if we take a `WickContraction n` `c` and apply the inverse of `extractEquiv` to get a `WickContraction (n+1)` (by inserting `i` into `c`'s uncontracted set), then the uncontracted part of this new `WickContraction (n+1)` is precisely the original `c`'s uncontracted set with `i` inserted.

Now, we have a lemma about how the `k`-th element of the uncontracted set relates to the original:

```tactics
@[simp]
lemma extractEquiv_apply_congr_symm_apply {n m : ℕ} (k : ℕ)
    (hnk : k < n.succ) (hkm : k < m.succ) (hnm : n = m) (c : WickContraction n)
    (i : c.uncontracted) : congr (by rw [hnm]) ((extractEquiv ⟨k, hkm⟩
    (congr (by rw [hnm]) ((extractEquiv ⟨k, hnk⟩).symm ⟨c, i⟩)))).1 = c := by
  subst hnm
  simp
```

This lemma is showing that applying the forward and backward directions of `extractEquiv` appropriately recovers the original `c`. It's a technical lemma ensuring the equivalence is well-behaved with respect to congruences.

