```tactics
lemma extractEquiv_equiv {c1 c2 : (c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted}
    (h : c1.1 = c2.1) (ho : c1.2 = uncontractedCongr (by rw [h]) c2.2) : c1 = c2 := by
  cases c1
  cases c2
  simp_all only [Sigma.mk.inj_iff]
  simp only at h
  subst h
  simp only [uncontractedCongr, Equiv.optionCongr_apply, heq_eq_eq, true_and]
  rename_i a
  match a with
  | none => simp
  | some a =>
    simp only [Option.map_some, Option.some.injEq]
    ext
    simp
```

This lemma establishes an equivalence between two pairs `(c, k)` where `c` is a `WickContraction n` and `k` is an `Option c.uncontracted`. The proof proceeds by case analysis on the structure of the pairs.

Next, we define the `extractEquiv` equivalence between `WickContraction n.succ` and `(c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted`.

```tactics
/-- The equivalence between `WickContraction n.succ` and the sigma type
  `(c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted` formed by inserting
  and erasing elements from a contraction. -/
def extractEquiv (i : Fin n.succ) : WickContraction n.succ ≃
    (c : WickContraction n) × Option c.uncontracted where
  toFun := fun c => ⟨erase c i, getDualErase c i⟩
  invFun := fun ⟨c, j⟩ => insertAndContractNat c i j
  left_inv f := by
    simp
  right_inv f := by
    refine extractEquiv_equiv ?_ ?_
    simp only [insertAndContractNat_erase]
    simp only [Nat.succ_eq_add_one]
    have h1 := insertAndContractNat_getDualErase f.fst i f.snd
    exact insertAndContractNat_getDualErase _ i _
```

This defines the `extractEquiv` equivalence. The forward direction (`toFun`) maps a `WickContraction n.succ` to a pair `(erase c i, getDualErase c i)`. The inverse direction (`invFun`) maps a pair `(c, j)` back to `insertAndContractNat c i j`. The lemmas `left_inv` and `right_inv` prove that these operations are inverses.

Next, we have a lemma about the uncontracted part of the equivalence.

```tactics
lemma extractEquiv_symm_none_uncontracted (i : Fin n.succ) (c : WickContraction n) :
    ((extractEquiv i).symm ⟨c, none⟩).uncontracted =
    (Insert.insert i (c.uncontracted.map i.succAboveEmb)) := by
  exact insertAndContractNat_none_uncontracted c i
```

This lemma shows what the uncontracted part looks like when we take the symmetric version of the equivalence and apply it to `(c, none)`. The result is `insert i (c.uncontracted.map i.succAboveEmb)`.

Next, we have a lemma about applying congruences to the equivalence.

```tactics
@[simp]
lemma extractEquiv_apply_congr_symm_apply {n m : ℕ} (k : ℕ)
    (hnk : k < n.succ) (hkm : k < m.succ) (hnm : n = m) (c : WickContraction n)
    (i : c.uncontracted) : congr (by rw [hnm]) ((extractEquiv ⟨k, hkm⟩
    (congr (by rw [hnm]) ((extractEquiv ⟨k, hnk⟩).symm ⟨c, i⟩)))).1 = c := by
  subst hnm
  simp
```

This lemma shows that applying a congruence through the equivalence and its symmetric version results in the original `c`.

